      },
      "date": "2012-08-27 18:22:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5: Looks good to me, but someone else must approve\n\nThe patch looks OK, but there should be a test case to exercise all of the failure cases that John could originally break.\n\nIt should be possible to trigger the failures using \"multiop\" instead of introducing the new \"sys_*\" tools that John was using, to avoid proliferation of testing binaries.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "64aa0e64b32fdadefef985bcdc2fa9427f2c4b73",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 177,
        "name": "John Hammond",
        "email": "jhammond@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "jhammond"
      },
      "date": "2012-08-28 01:09:20.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 5:\n\nThere are still some issues with accessing perversely crafted fids.\n\n[sanity]$ stat .lustre/fid/[0x1:0x2:0x3]\n\nMessage from syslogd@r62-l23 at Aug 27 14:54:50 ...\n kernel:LustreError: 8455:0:(lustre_idl.h:785:lu_fid_eq()) ASSERTION( (fid_is_igif(f1) || fid_is_idif(f1)) || fid_ver(f1) == 0 ) failed: [0x1:0x2:0x3]\n\nMessage from syslogd@r62-l23 at Aug 27 14:54:50 ...\n kernel:LustreError: 8455:0:(lustre_idl.h:785:lu_fid_eq()) LBUG\n\nThis may be due only to a discrepancies between the checks in fid_is_sane() (called in obf_lookup()) and the checks in lu_fid_eq().  Perhaps a good workaround would be to replace the call to fid_is_sane() with a check that the FID belongs to the \"normal\" sequence range.  Otherwise it would be worthwhile to check accesses against FIDs from all possible seq ranges with appropriate OID and version combinations (zero and non-zero).",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 5
    },
    {
      "id": "1993d4e5c2e8d29d72de686a4f11a61a60de40ec",
